The closest competitors in Cannon are none while in Nikon, there's D5100 and D3200. Well, first thing. Give anyone who owns a Nikon, they will accept without doubt that the Cannon UI is more user friendly. This actually helps when you are in a situation to capture a rare pic and you don't have much time to adjust manual settings. Nikon D3200 pictures comes with a yellowish haze under fluorescent light. That's actually annoying. Nikon D5100 has built in HDR which is good. Cannon lenses (55-250 IS)are cheaper compared to Nikon (75 - 300 VR) D3200 comes with a 24mpx sensor while this one has 18. D5100 has 16 MPX. Though its not a big concern anywhere. It is better if you have higher MPX for a perfect shot. Video quality is pretty good with Cannon, (useless info if you want just the pictures). Overall, a combination of 5100 and 3200 would be the perfect one. But since it does not exist, we go for something that's marginally less in a few aspects. If you are looking for a specific application for your SLR, you may go for 3200 or 5100. Otherwise Cannon would be a wise choice. PS: Just see the prices for Cannon 55-250 IS lens before purchasing. You will need it for sure. The question would be whether to go for it later or buy it immediately. Whichever works out cheaper, go for it.
