I have been able to get my hands on one since past 3 days, using it along with a 75-300 mm 4-5.6 and a 50mm 1.8 lenses. Camera looks compact for a DSLR. Neatly designed menus and has creative effects like toy camera, grainy black and white, soft focus and miniature effects. The swivel LCD is nice and bright, and highly useful in shooting at difficult angles. Given such a short duration, I wont be able to write comprehensively about this camera but here are some pros and cons I found. Pros: -Compact body, feels like advance superzoom cameras -3.7 frames Is quiet good (though it slows down at high ISOs) -You can zoom into the frame to check sharpness of focus. Button on top right of the back side -Flip screen LCD highly useful - Upto 12800 ISO can be used (visible and distinct noise at 12800ISO, 6400 recommended) -in camera creative effects, though wished there were more. Cons: -exposure value adjustment and bracketing buried deep inside menus -Only 1 cross type autofocus point (more time to focus on moving subjects) though there are total 9 autofocus points. -manual focus must with f 1.8 50mm lens, struggles otherwise -auto white balance tends to favor warmer side, gives orange tint while shooting under incandescent light -ONLY 440 shots per charge Overall a good DSLR for beginners, make sure you get a normal(50mm) lens and a zoom (75-300mm) lenses which cost about additional 21,000 more. If you are not too much into technicalities and want a dslr to start with. Go for it.
